# Security and Hardening

## Overview

Securit…4701 tokens truncated…minal` tool over SSH. After the user confirms the source result, apply that chosen source to every requested target host only after a dry-run preview. Do not stop at "source committed/pushed" when a paired target was involved; complete the remote fast-forward, targeted dry-run, apply, and clean-status verification unless a safety gate or exact blocker stops the run.

## Device Discovery

When the user does not name the target hosts, discover the sync set from the live NetBird inventory instead of hard-coding device names:

1. Run `netbird status --json` locally.
2. Identify the local FQDN and every connected peer FQDN beginning with `yusoofs-`.
3. Exclude the local FQDN from the remote list. For each peer, verify SSH reachability and `chezmoi` availability before treating it as a target.
4. Include every verified peer in the machine matrix. Record a connected but unusable peer with its non-sensitive blocker; do not silently drop it. Do not treat disconnected peers as available unless the user explicitly names them.

Use the discovered FQDN or an equivalent configured SSH alias. An explicitly named host is always in scope, even if it is unavailable.

## Completion Gate

A chezmoi sync is not complete until every machine in scope has been verified. When the user does not name targets, the scope is the local machine plus every currently available NetBird peer discovered by the Device Discovery procedure. Never infer a fixed paired device name from memory or the skill text.

Before any final success reply, build and report a machine matrix that includes each local and remote target. Every row must have current evidence for:
- source Git revision
- `chezmoi status --path-style=absolute`
- `chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose`
- source Git status

If any machine was not checked, did not fast-forward, did not apply, or still has unexpected drift, do not say "done", "complete", "clean", or "synced". Report the task as blocked or incomplete with the exact missing machine and command.

## Quick Reference

| Purpose | Command |
|---|---|
| Show pending changes | `chezmoi status` |
| Show absolute pending changes | `chezmoi status --path-style=absolute` |
| Show terminal-only target-vs-destination diff | `chezmoi diff --use-builtin-diff --no-pager --no-tty TARGET` |
| Show ignored entries | `chezmoi ignored` |
| Show source directory | `chezmoi source-path` |
| Show target source path | `chezmoi source-path TARGET` |
| Re-add modified files preserving `encrypted_` | `chezmoi re-add TARGET` |
| Add or replace from live destination | `chezmoi add TARGET` |
| Force one file into source | `chezmoi add --force TARGET` |
| Mark template/private/etc. | `chezmoi chattr private,template TARGET` |
| Merge live/source/target | `chezmoi merge TARGET` |
| Preview apply | `chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose` |
| Apply selected source path | `chezmoi apply --source-path SOURCE_PATH` |

## Procedure

1. **Snapshot local status first.**
   ```bash
   chezmoi status --path-style=absolute
   chezmoi diff --use-builtin-diff --no-pager --no-tty
   chezmoi source-path
   git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" status --short
   ```

2. **Discover remote targets when none are named.** Run `netbird status --json`, resolve the available `yusoofs-` peers as described in Device Discovery, and list the resulting target set before any write.

3. **Snapshot each requested or discovered remote host independently.** Replace `REMOTE_HOST` with the resolved SSH alias or host.
   ```bash
   ssh REMOTE_HOST 'chezmoi status --path-style=absolute && chezmoi diff --use-builtin-diff --no-pager --no-tty && chezmoi source-path && git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" status --short'
   ```

4. **Classify each changed target.** Use the two `chezmoi status` columns correctly:
   - First column: difference between last state written by chezmoi and actual live state.
   - Second column: difference between live state and target state, i.e. what `chezmoi apply` would do.
   - Prefer files with live modifications in the first column as candidates to sync back to source.

5. **Inspect the current source path and attributes before changing source.**
   ```bash
   chezmoi source-path TARGET
   ```
   Then inspect the source filename. Treat markers as live source metadata, not decoration:
   - Prefixes include `dot_`, `private_`, `encrypted_`, `executable_`, `create_`, `modify_`, `remove_`, `exact_`, `symlink_`, `run_`, `once_`, `onchange_`, `before_`, `after_`.
   - Suffixes include `.tmpl`; encrypted files may also have encryption suffixes such as `.age` when age is configured.
   - Attribute order matters; do not rename markers casually.

6. **Pick the safest source-update path per file, but do not run it yet.**
   - Plain non-template file: `chezmoi re-add TARGET` is usually safest and preserves `encrypted_`.
   - Template (`.tmpl`): do **not** rely on `chezmoi re-add`; chezmoi will not overwrite templates. Manually merge the live value into the template source after inspecting `chezmoi source-path TARGET`.
   - Encrypted file: prefer `chezmoi re-add TARGET` so `encrypted_` is preserved; if changing attributes, use `chezmoi chattr` instead of ad-hoc renames.
   - Create/modify/remove/symlink/script/exact entries: do not flatten them into regular files. Preserve the type marker (`create_`, `modify_`, `remove_`, `symlink_`, `run_` with `once_`/`onchange_`) unless the user explicitly approves a type change.
   - A single unconditional plain-file replacement may use `chezmoi add --force TARGET`, but only after confirming the source attributes are still correct.

7. **Walk through every drift with a compact prompt.**
   Build the full drift list for yourself, then present one changed target or tightly related group at a time. For each item, show only:
   - target path and source path
   - one short evidence summary from the focused diff
   - the recommendation

   Summarize private config diffs without printing secrets, tokens, bearer headers, cookies, or literal credential values. If a secret-like value appears in a diff, redact it in the user-facing matrix and prefer source-path/status evidence over verbatim output.

   Execute the user's chosen decision immediately for that item, verify the drift cleared or was intentionally deferred, then move to the next item. Do not present a giant table and ask for all choices at once unless the user asks for batch mode.

   Use these rules only to form recommendations:
   - If only one host changed live state and source attributes match intent, recommend syncing that host to source.
   - If both hosts changed the same target differently, recommend `chezmoi merge TARGET` on the host with the desired live baseline or manually merging in source.
   - If source has a template, encrypted file, script, symlink, or `exact_` directory, preserve that structure and port only the intended content change.
   - If a change would delete history or stats, back up first and ask before applying.

8. **Apply the user-confirmed updates to source.**
   ```bash
   chezmoi re-add TARGET
   git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" diff -- SOURCE_PATH
   ```
   For templates or special entries, use `read_file` on the source path and `patch` the source file, then review with Git diff through the `terminal` tool.

9. **Converge every live or target machine in scope.**
   When a remote live state is authoritative, first update source from that winning host:
   ```bash
   ssh REMOTE_HOST 'chezmoi re-add TARGET && git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" diff -- SOURCE_PATH'
   ```
   If remote source cannot push/pull directly, stop and report the exact blocker instead of fabricating synchronization.
   After source is reviewed, pull or otherwise make the confirmed source available on each target host, dry-run the apply, then apply only the selected source path:
   ```bash
   chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose --source-path SOURCE_PATH
   chezmoi apply --source-path SOURCE_PATH
   ssh REMOTE_HOST 'chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose --source-path SOURCE_PATH && chezmoi apply --source-path SOURCE_PATH'
   ```
   Then re-run `chezmoi status --path-style=absolute` on every requested target host. If more drift appears inside the approved target set, continue with focused source-path mapping and apply it too. If broad apply is blocked by unrelated drift, changed-since-last-written prompts, or a directory diff edge case, switch to per-file `chezmoi source-path TARGET` plus `chezmoi apply --dry-run --force --source-path SOURCE_PATH` and `chezmoi apply --force --source-path SOURCE_PATH` for the selected targets. Create missing parent directories only when the source path maps to a file that should exist and the directory creation is non-destructive.

10. **Sync source Git only after review.**
   ```bash
   git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" status --short
   git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" diff
   ```
   Commit/push only when the user asked for it or the current workflow explicitly requires it.

11. **Preview the final effect before applying anywhere, then prove clean state.**
    ```bash
    chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose
    ssh REMOTE_HOST 'chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose'
    ```
    If the final broad dry-run fails because of an already-handled target directory or an unrelated prompt, run a targeted dry-run/apply/status loop for each selected source path, then report any remaining unrelated drift separately instead of calling the sync complete.

12. **Final reply gate.** Before sending the final reply, run the completion gate for every machine in scope. The final reply must include the machine matrix for the local device and every discovered or explicitly named target.

## Pitfalls

- `chezmoi re-add` preserves `encrypted_` but will not overwrite templates; use manual template edits for `.tmpl` files.
- `chezmoi add` can replace an existing source entry and can lose intent if you ignore filename attributes first.
- `exact_` directories are statefully synced; adding/removing live files can cause source removals and later target deletions.
- `chezmoi status` has two columns; confusing them can turn an apply-needed file into a source-sync candidate.
- Source filenames encode behavior. Do not strip `private_`, `encrypted_`, `executable_`, `.tmpl`, `create_`, `modify_`, `remove_`, `exact_`, `symlink_`, `run_once_`, or `run_onchange_` just because the live path lacks those words.
- Remote and local hosts may intentionally differ through templates; a rendered difference is not automatically a conflict, but it still belongs in the confirmation matrix.
- Never auto-resolve a drift just because one recommendation is obvious. The point of this skill is for the user to choose what goes into source before it fans out to targets.
- A source update is not complete while another live or target machine in scope remains dirty. Finish fast-forward/apply/status on every requested target before reporting success.
- Avoid making the user parse a large drift table. The default user experience is one item, one compact choice, one verification, then the next item.
- Avoid plain `chezmoi diff` when the repo config sets `diff.command`; use `--use-builtin-diff --no-pager --no-tty` so the run stays terminal-only and noninteractive.
- Treat private config diffs as sensitive. Do not paste literal tokens, bearer headers, cookies, or private key material into chat.
- If `chezmoi add` ignores files, check both `chezmoi ignored` and Git ignore rules before assuming chezmoi is broken.

## Verification

Run this through the `terminal` tool and confirm the remaining output is expected before reporting success:

```bash
chezmoi status && chezmoi apply --dry-run --verbose && git -C "$(chezmoi source-path)" status --short
